<br>
That's not to say that any of the consoles are &quot;better&quot; hardware than the PC market. It's just the opposite, really, but PCs are generalized hardware. In order to match the performance of those few, specialized, juiced up components of the console, you have to buy a PC that's overkill in most other areas. To make a long story short, I'd take that minimum requirement with a generous grain of salt.<br>
<br>
Now then...../rant on<br>
<br>
But really, my big issue with FFXI isn't so much about the hardware or the game mechanics, it's that I'm getting kind of cynical about the game series itself. Don't get me wrong, they're still fun to play, but the &quot;old school&quot; FF crowd is roughly in their mid 20s now. Square hasn't figured that out yet. They really need to work on plot, character development, and decent dialogue. Case in point - take a look at Vagrant Story some time. Whether you love or hate the gameplay, you have to agree that it had a much more &quot;grown up&quot; feel to it. They don't have to make FF all dark and gritty, but they could stand to make characters a little older, have them behave and react much more realistically, and come up with some plots with real depth. FF4, 5, 6... were all fine when I was 12, but the age difference is becoming very apparent. All I know is that for quite some time, whenever I've played the latest FF, I feel like I should run out and buy bubble gum and glitter pens....and I'm a guy <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> . A little age regression is fun once in a while, but....<br>
